nhanes_data<-NHANES[,c('Age','Height','BMI')]
age_17_and_under<-subset(nhanes_data, (Age>1) & (Age<=17))

#Removing Missing Values
age_17_and_under<-na.omit(age_17_and_under)
table(is.na(age_17_and_under))
## 
## FALSE 
##  6660
#Doing some exploratory data analysis to see which kind of model would best describe the relationship between the given variables
ggpairs(age_17_and_under, columns = c(1,2,3))

#code to fit gam model on the data
fit<-gam(BMI ~ s(Age) + s(Height),  data = age_17_and_under, method = "REML")
summary(fit)
## 
## Family: gaussian 
## Link function: identity 
## 
## Formula:
## BMI ~ s(Age) + s(Height)
##

## R-sq.(adj) =  0.366   Deviance explained = 36.8%
## -REML = 6339.4  Scale est. = 17.527    n = 2220
plot(fit)

The GAM plots shows theres something the linear model isnt capturing since it isnt a straight line. So a gam model seems to be the right choice for this data

#Plotting residuals of the model against the fitted values
age_17_and_under.gam.df = augment(fit)
ggplot(age_17_and_under.gam.df, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method.args = list(degree = 1))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

The residual plots looks pretty good centred around 0 with no major trend to it.

Question 4

xgrid <-  seq(min(age_17_and_under$Age), max(age_17_and_under$Age), 0.5)
ygrid <-  seq(min(age_17_and_under$Height), max(age_17_and_under$Height), 0.5)
# Generate a dataframe with every possible combination of Age and Height
data.fit <-  expand.grid(Age = xgrid, Height = ygrid)
# Feed the dataframe into the gam model and receive a matrix output with estimates of BMI for each combination of Age and Height
data.predict <-  predict(fit, newdata = data.fit)
data.plot.df = data.frame(data.fit, BMI_Predicted = as.vector(data.predict))
ggplot(data.plot.df, aes(x = Age, y = Height, z = BMI_Predicted, fill = BMI_Predicted)) +
  geom_raster() +
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = "RdYlBu") +
  geom_contour(binwidth=1)+ggtitle("Contour Plot of height with age for predicted BMI ")

Research Question 1:How does average BMI vary with height and age for children 17 and under? The plot is saying that the lowest average BMIs are for low age and low height whereas the highest average BMIs are for high age and high heights. For any age, the plot gets redder as we go up, so conditional on age, the models predicted BMI tends to go up with height.**

Research Question 2: Is BMI a good measure of body mass for children? BMI is often justified as a measure of body mass for adults because the average BMI doesnt vary much by height for them But for children, we see from the contour plot that this is quite the opposite for all age groups. With increase in height, the average BMI increases for almost all age groups in children. So we cannot ignore the height aspect here and hence BMI is not a good measure of body mass for children.
